[Java][1] is a dynamic language. Current version (at time of writing) is 20. When I run your command with Java 20, I get an error:
&gt; script engine for language js can not be found

In fact, the documentation for [jrunscript][2] states:
&gt; This tool is experimental and unsupported.

However, since it appears to be working in the Java version that you are using (which I could not ascertain from your question), and since it is using [streams][3], you can add a *filter*. So try the following:
```none
java.util.Arrays.asList(javax.net.ssl.SSLServerSocketFactory.getDefault().getSupportedCipherSuites()).stream().filter(s -&gt; &quot;TLS_DHE_RSA_WITH_AES_256_GCM_SHA384&quot;.equals(s) || &quot;TLS_ECDHE_RSA_WITH_AES_256_GCM_SHA384&quot;.equals(s)).forEach(println)
```
I suggest that you write a Java [class][4] and use the [java][5] command. Here is an example:
```java
import java.util.Arrays;
import java.util.List;

import javax.net.ssl.SSLServerSocketFactory;

public class MyCiphers {

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        List&lt;String&gt; desired = List.of(&quot;TLS_DHE_RSA_WITH_AES_256_GCM_SHA384&quot;,
                                       &quot;TLS_ECDHE_RSA_WITH_AES_256_GCM_SHA384&quot;);
        SSLServerSocketFactory fact = (SSLServerSocketFactory) SSLServerSocketFactory.getDefault();
        String[] supported = fact.getSupportedCipherSuites();
        Arrays.stream(supported)
              .filter(s -&gt; desired.contains(s))
              .forEach(System.out::println);
    }
}
